Date: Friday, March 24th

Time: 7:30pm

Address: Dramatists Guild, Mary Rodgers Room 1501 Broadway (at 43rd Street), Suite 710

Description: Set in the contemporary world, Jane is a struggling writer in her 30’s addicted to ice cream. Bill, her partner, wants a “normal” life. His disappointment in her ability to succumb to a conventional lifestyle leads hike to offer up an ultimatum - either they purchase a winning lottery ticket from the bodega across the street or have a baby.

Friday Night Footlights is a gratis program, created and moderated by the Dramatists Guild, that supports dramatists by enabling them to hold a public reading of a new work that is currently in development, with an optional feedback session following the reading. Back in 1989 I had a lot of guts and a whole lot of hair. And when I walk around NYC these days, the same streets I walked back then, I think about that girl. How scared she was and what courage she had. There was nothing to fall back on. No sofa to go sleep on. No “home for the holidays.” I became totally focused on working harder than anyone else, because I thought it was the only thing keeping me from slipping back into that place of “non-work.” Now, I still work hard but I have come to value resting. Giving myself joy. Giving myself people who make me laugh and putting myself in the way of delight. Life is hard. Laugh harder. #dontlettheturkeysgetyoudown

There’s no place I’d rather be, than hashing out a new play with these wonderful artists.

Hey everyone!! I’m super excited to start teaching at Michael Howard Studios and wanted to share my excitement with you!

About the workshop: I’ve put together a full compendium of “what works and what doesn’t” based on 45 years in this business. It’s so important to “take care of your business” while taking care of yourself as an artist. It’s a skill that isn’t often taught. Rather, actors leave it up to “the universe” to decide their career path for them. You can do better, I promise you.

This class is based directly on my experience as a student of Michael Howard as well as what I’ve learned from applying what he taught in my work since. In both the monthly class and the workshop, I talk about the role of the actor in society and how to care for yourself as an artist.

Thank you so much Youlim!! 

I feel lucky to get to work with actors. It is a privilege to have their trust and to get to guide them toward their own sacred space within. The safe space. The creative space. We all have it, but some of us NEED to be in it more than others. Those of us who are called are the artists class.  We are our own unique group of people, and come in all shapes, sizes, ages, cultures, belief systems, and skin colors.

Actors are a unique tribe within the artists class. Because what we do seems so “easy,” so “vain,” we are mocked and ridiculed, envied and attacked. It comes with the territory of being different.

And because what we do, in its purest form (and with good writing) is hold a mirror up to nature. We are here to serve, not to judge. To observe and reflect what we see, to express all aspects of the human experience. 

Acting is a practice. It is a life long commitment that comes with its own rhythms. Rhythms I’ve lived for and with all my life. It is my joy to share this way of being an actor with you.

The world needs more artists. We are the flower planters in a world of bombs.

I invite you to join me on Saturdays to “drop in” and explore your actor self. 

(Here’s the big secret: it’s a lot of fun!!!)

Hey! I am excited to share I just got cast in the lead role in “Shirley Valentine” at Cape May Stage in Cape May, NJ.  Now to learn 45 pages of a monologue. Omg. In a Liverpool accent. Yikes. Did you know the slang name for the accent used by people from Liverpool is “Scouse”? I did not. 

“Scouse (/skaʊs/ SKOWSS), formally known as Liverpool English or Merseyside English, is an accent and dialect of English associated with Liverpool and the surrounding county of Merseyside. The Scouse accent is highly distinctive; having been influenced heavily by Irish and Welsh immigrants who arrived via the Liverpool docks, it has little in common with the accents of its neighbouring regions or the rest of England. Scouse is also a general term for this pan-ethnic community or Liverpudlians in general. The accent is named after scouse, a stew eaten by sailors and locals.” - Thank you Wikipedia

I’m so excited to share with you these photos I discovered yesterday from the show that brought me to NYC as a teenager: “Happy Birthday and Other Humiliations.” 

Book and Lyrics by Judith Viorst, music by Shelly Markham, starring Bonnie Franklin. Directed by Alan Johnson.

After doing the workshop in Los Angeles (which is where they found me) the producers raised the money to bring the show to a full production at the John Drew Theatre in East Hampton. 

My mom and I got ourselves to NY after they let us know they wanted me to continue in the role. It changed my life and I’m forever grateful.

That said, to say I had no idea what I was getting into would be an understatement. I was not only a rather naive girl, I was raised in such a protective environment I hardly knew anyone outside my own family, which mainly consisted of two people. 

Fortunately, I had one gift: the gift of self-discipline. And when the producers showed me how to apply it to the preparation and rehearsal process, I did so with dedicated effort. This led to a golden moment: Bob Fosse coming backstage to shake my hand and tell me I did a good job. I’ll never forget it. His hands were huge and his energy was still such a force. A powerful presence to say the least.

At the time, I was living with my mother in a studio apartment, sleeping on futons. There was no “home elsewhere.” We had been spiraling financially for some time. This was it. The pressure, you might say, was not unsubstantial.

I am so grateful for the memories of how kind Bonnie, Shelley, and Judith were to me. They seemed to see my naïveté and overwhelm and were gentle with me, despite their own pressures and concerns. I’ll always be grateful to them for that kindness, and for the incredible opportunity they gave me. 

Picture 1: top row: Shelly Markham and me. Bottom row: Judith Viorst and Bonnie Franklin (star of the original “One Day at a Time).

One of the most magical moments I’ve had in my career was being in “My Favorite Year,” directed by Richard Benjamin and starring Peter O’Toole.

I played Tess Swann - the daughter of O’Toole’s character, Alan Swann.

“My Favorite Year” is a hilarious and wonderful film that captures an important part of the end of one era and the beginning of live television in New York City.

Had a lovely interview with Jacob Young on his podcast yesterday morning. Should be airing soon. 

He asked some wonderful questions. One of them touched on something I’ve been thinking about for a while… the effort to be self-validating. 

There is a tendency to think we need a cheering section, and certainly the support of friends and family can make a huge difference. But if we don’t cheer ourselves on, do we even hear their voices?

Today I am embracing all… even the pain that inevitably comes with living a full life with an open heart.

Today, I am dedicating myself to walking my path the way I feel is right for me, whether or not anyone agrees with it. And I will gently cheer myself on along the way.

Sure, I will fuck up sometimes. But I can only hope other people will see the goodness in me, in my efforts. I do try very hard to keep my heart open. To say “YES” to things that have the sparkle in them, the sparkle that always delivers some wonderful richness, when investigated.

It’s a practice. Starting now, and now, and now.

Those are my thoughts today…. Happy Tuesday!

This play is one of the hardest shows I’ve ever done… two hours on stage alone, 41 pages of a fast moving monologue, with multiple characters and accents. To get this kind of feedback from audience members is worth sharing because it shows that it can be done and done well! 

It has not been easy and has taken enormous discipline. The month before rehearsals started I shut down all socializing and just worked on the play. The month before that I also had very limited interactions. However, I kept teaching both months as that has been an incredible source of inspiration for me. 

As I do this play I’m using all the things I teach, so I can go back to my students and tell them “here is how this works. I know, because I’ve done it!”

Thank you to those of you who held my hand, cheered me on, ran lines with me, and kept on being kind and strong when I staggered. The beauty of humanity shows itself in those moments of kindness and I’m deeply grateful for them. My success is also yours, for I carry you in my heart always.

The play only runs through July 2nd. Cape May is a gorgeous little town. I hope to see you soon! Make sure to wait around to say hi after the show!

I made a full length documentary film without having taken any class or gone to film school. It was my film school. Was it hard? Yes. Did I get yelled at and belittled? You bet I did. Did I finish it and win awards and get distribution and ensure that is was seen? You betcha.

Did the distributors screw me? Yep. Did I get new ones? Indeed I did. Did it make a difference in people’s lives? It certainly did.

Did I blame anyone or screw anyone over? No, I did not. I’m a solid and ferocious defender of forgiveness and letting shit go.

So why do I sometimes still feel fear around my work? Why do I fear getting hurt? I’ve been hurt to the core. Multiple times. Kicked in the pants. Hard. Okay. 

Some people say that if you’re not nervous it isn’t meaningful. I think that might not be the key. I think the key is practicing courage. But there’s more…

Here’s what you gotta do.

GET UP.

The one thing I know is true is that you gotta be a fighter. 

When I think like a pro baseball player and not let anyone convince me that I can’t do something, by God it gets done.

I had the wind knocked out of my sails last year. Okay. That happened. So what. 

GET UP.

Punch something (not someone). Scream. Give yourself a chance to vent. But don’t hang out there.

And don’t ever quit. 

You gotta find the fight in you and believe it is right and good and true, deep down in your belly.

Doesn’t mean that you aren’t also good and kind and a sensitive artist. It means you aren’t a victim. Roadkill. And you can’t be, in this world. No sir-ee. No. No. No.

Ya gotta have the hide of a rhinoceros and the soul of a child. You have to allow yourself to be tough and still dance in the sand.

That’s my advice from me to me and I hope you get something out of it.

When I was a kid I got to go to a wonderful riding camp called Rawhide Ranch. The first horse I was assigned was named Holygold.

I’d shovel poop until the dirt was so clean there was nothing to do but rake patterns. 

The people that worked here were good and strong. They encouraged me to be courageous and do hard things, helped me focus my strength towards skills that made me proud.

I learned not only how to ride a horse bareback, but by the time I left I could drive a buggy, gallop in a saddle, barrel race, and do some vaulting: jumping onto and standing on a horse as it loped.

I learned to milk cows and goats, and knew all the parts of all the animals I had the privilege to care for.

This place was a light during a very dark time in my youth, and I will forever be grateful and thankful for it.

So if someone gives you the opportunity to shovel shit, don’t be afraid. There might be a pony in there somewhere. And even if there isn’t, there is pride to be had in hard work well done.

I was a spokesperson for these little dolls when I was around eleven or twelve or so. The wardrobe person had to wrap an ace bandage around my breasts so I’d be perfectly flat. It was odd and a little embarrassing but my mother had been fussing with my body and hair for so long it wasn’t completely traumatizing, it just made it a bit difficult to move or breathe. 🤦‍♀️

In writing this, I can see how shocking this must sound. Trust me, it wasn’t easy to live it. 

As a child, I got used to pain. Dancing through blisters from tap shoes, wardrobe fittings where strangers poked at me, teachers stretching me until muscles popped, and my mother… always there with a new horror. Whether it was curlers that were too tight or trying to make me take enemas, or spanking me … my childhood was full of humiliation in a myriad of ways.

By the time I was 19 I couldn’t stand to be touched.

I look back now and think of myself as a circus performer. I’m more flexible and stronger than most people, in ways that are hard to explain but absolutely true.

One thing I’ve learned is that gentleness, tenderness is more important than pain, and more powerful.  Of course, you need to be able to be disciplined in life, but you also must be able to be tender with yourself and others. 

Tenderness allows the heart to soften and the soul to expand its invisible listening ear. It makes connection possible, whether you are connecting with yourself or someone else.

As an actor, tenderness toward yourself is essential. You need discipline to get your ass on stage but you’re not going to crack that oyster of your emotional center open by yelling at it. Getting to the pearl is only achievable by being tender with yourself.

When your heart feels pain, this is even more important. “Soft soft soft,” as my friend Ronda used to say. 

Don’t get tough with your own heart or others hearts. That’s a dead end road. No bueno.

That’s my wisdom for the day, inspired by friends. Thank you friends. 🩷

#tenderness

This is me and my mother. She was a lot of things. Hilarious, wild, tough, brilliant, controlling, cruel, a real smart ass, and occasionally nuttier than a fruit cake. 

My favorite moments were when we sat and talked about philosophy or poetry. She was good like that.

I bought a mouse puppet on a day I was being forced to be a lady and walk through some gardens. You can tell the gesture the mouse is making. 

That puppet got me through the day. It had a lot to say and somehow she let it speak. 

She was a rebel against her family. I rebelled against her. There was no way that wasn’t going to happen. 

Yet when she died I howled like a wild animal trying to bring down the moon. 

That grief haunted me for years and can still be wrested out of my chest on occasion. It’s a part of me now. I accept it.

I’m actually grateful she was my mother. God knows she wasn’t easy, and it’s absolutely true I had to raise her like she was my own child, but she’s a soul I’m glad to have known. She was, at best, resilient. And surviving her made me so as well.

#mama

I went to bed thinking about taking responsibility for how I treat others and slept well. No matter what I’ve lived through, reacting with fear or anger is no bueno. I have to be the center point for peace, for kindness. That’s it. No negotiation.

Of course, I have experienced both sides of this coin. 

It is much, much better on your own heart to be kind. It doesn’t matter if it’s not reciprocated. 

I have found it’s important to stop negotiating with justifications and stick to my principles. 

Be kind. Period.

To be kind doesn’t mean you’re a sap and let people walk all over you.  It’s a form of understanding that life is hard for everyone. It’s loving people, even when they are a hot mess.

I woke up feeling good. Peaceful. 

I then started thinking about how when talented people become famous there always seems to be someone around to convince them that they should not be kind. That they should be cynical and cruel and explore a dark road. And it always turns out that the dark road does more harm to their talent and light than good. 

They suffer enormously from this choice. 

I have had my experience with this as well. 

A bright light attracts moths. I call them “the light eaters.”

It is VERY important not to let the moths have their way. One’s own light is too important. 

The only way to handle them is to shine so bright they burn up if they get too close. Tough luck for Skippy.

Keep shining. It’s actually important. Shining gives people hope. And in this world that seems to trip over its own two feet time and again, hope is a precious commodity. Don’t underestimate it’s power.

And don’t let anyone convince you otherwise.

Just watched this beautiful film by Hal Hartley called “Trust” on the Criterion Collection. I remember watching Hartley’s films in the ‘90’s, then walking for hours around downtown NY. The film somehow slowed down time.

It gave me the pleasure of experiencing the world at a less frenetic pace, where every small thing seemed to have a bit more meaning, which is one of my favorite states of being. 

“Trust” is a love story about two people who come from similarly difficult and violent parents. They decide that trust + respect + admiration = love.

I love this film because of its honesty wrapped in a very specific language style that is a product of the writers imagination. Writers who build specific and captivating worlds with language are my favorites and deserve all the flowers. They transport us and pierce us with truths wrapped in honey.

When I put myself in the path of their work, it can feel like I’m standing close to a monk ringing a giant bell. Another feeling I love.

Should you be interested to read more, there are some good essays on his website, HalHartley.com

In particular I recommend “Be Good to Her and She’ll Be Good to You” by Bell Hooks.

“It was odd, she thought, that if one was alone one lent to inanimate things; trees, streams, flowers; felt they expressed one; felt they became one; felt they knew one, in a sense were one; felt an irrational tenderness thus (she looked at that long steady light) as for oneself.”

- Virginia Woolf

I am feeling a bit like Persephone these days. 

I don’t think there is a whole lot more frightening than one’s imagination. It’s like seeing shadows on the wall. Down in the underworld, I looked for the source of them… and found … there was nothing there. Just a picture from a moment long ago. A shadow dancing.

I find this realization a huge relief.

This is how the past deceives us, controls us.

Awakening to the fact that everyone has shadows that frighten them has somehow made me love people even more. 

I’ve had two missions in life. One has been to be free of the control of my past and the other has been a commitment to being an artist. Because what else can I be? It’s the core of who I am. 

I am discovering that the two walk hand in hand.

I’m no saint. I’ve walked in the gutter. Taken a bath and a long nap there. But something new is happening to my spirit and my heart and my mind. I’m waking up. And in awakening, finding more love and strength and kindness and patience than I knew I had in me.

And even though it’s been a hard road… and sometimes very painful, it’s been totally worth it.

Found this wonderful photo with me and David Canary (“Adam” from “All My Children.”)

When I am feeling happy and strong, I can forget I was ever sad. Then suddenly, someone or something can touch me and an ocean of sorrow begins to pour out. Some pain has a long tail.

This happened in a scene with Mike and I back in the late ‘90’s. It’s a fight scene where “Tad” is insisting “Dixie” get mad at him for cheating with “Liza.” 

It’s a beautifully written scene. Major shout out to the writers.

She eventually slaps him back into yesterday but not before expressing the agony that is connecting to her own broken heart.

Being this vulnerable in my work is not easy. Being this vulnerable in my life often does not feel safe. 

But I tell you what… I am damn proud of those scenes. Damn proud of that work. And that someone keeps finding it and reposting it is very moving to me. So thank you. 

Thank you to the people who watched my work, who keep coming around to support it and me. Sometimes I just float on your hands, you know. Maybe you don’t. But I do. Because we all shared this event, together. It’s never just me up there. 

Why act? When it can be so painful, why do it? 

I can only say that it has something to do with that floating feeling, when you and I know we are experiencing the same moment. That (perhaps) we might even be the same person, in a very specific way. And when that happens, it seems we are collectively experiencing a catharsis. And in that moment, the pain has meaning. And by giving it meaning, it may have words. And when it has words, we may have some understanding. 

And the Tiger of Pain relaxes his jaws for a moment. And then we might just experience a sense of love, for ourselves and others. It’s been known to happen.

So that’s why I do it. That’s what is on the other side. Big Love. Love that transcends pain, transcends betrayal, transcends even the body and time.

(And if at any point you get to laugh at the same time… my God… that’s just bliss.)

And when we meet, we both know have that shared moment forever. We “see” each other as we are. Transcendent. 

And isn’t that the best?

Fascinating fact: there is a bee on the ceiling of Grand Central.

It “…first appeared in 1613 on a celestial globe designed by Flemish astronomer Petrus Plancius, who referred to it as “Apes” or “the Bee”. The four stars that made up “Apes” were familiar to astronomers prior to this but were generally considered part of the Aries grouping and had never been specifically set aside on their own.

It’s not surprising that Plancius used these stars to make a new constellation, as this was something of a hobby of his.  Over his lifetime Plancius introduced 21 new constellations, many of which are still recognized by the International Astronomical Union (IAU)[1]….” - from bookwormhistory.com

Later, the constellation was referred to as a wasp, then a fly. Then it wasn’t included in the IAU’s list of constellations and the stars became a part of Aries. 

But I like to think of it as a bee on the ceiling, for my own reasons. Bees are nice, even if they sting it’s only when they are scared. They make the sweetness that heals and strengthens.

The world needs the bee, and I like to think Plancius thought so, too. 🐝

Good morning. I’m at the dentist. Decided to share what I look like without all the pretty bells and whistles that make up a stylish photo. 

I’ll be 54 this year and I don’t feel old at all. I have been told I am on the young side of old or the old side of young or something like that. But honestly, I don’t believe it or live by it. I think the spirit is timeless. I’ve met incredibly stupid old people and ridiculously smart young ones. I’ve known children with more wisdom than me, and old people with less common sense than a five year old.

The trick is to never stop learning. To be a student of life until you drop dead. Interested people are interesting people. 

And it’s relatively easy- all you need is the willingness to learn and change on your own determinism. That last part is especially important. You can only change if YOU want to change. 

Just keep this in mind: no one gets too old to learn a new way of being stupid.

What can I say in the face of these atrocities? I’m not a politician, or a great writer, or a political historian. I’ve had a crappy education and I try to avoid reading the news as much as possible (even though it still makes it’s way to me). I’m an actor. I act. I pretend for a living. 

I offer you my compassion. My empathy. My kindness. My knowledge that most people in this beautiful world are not savages. That most people are really quite good and lovely. And that most people are really and truly are doing the best they can.

The worst thing that can happen is that we start to see enemies everywhere. They are not everywhere. They are in very specific places and in fact… there actually aren’t that many of them.

What we need are strong minds, clear minds, and good hearts. We need logic and reason. We need action that does not destroy equally, but gets this thing under control. And we need sanity.

And then we need a ton of kindness, helping, outstretched hands. Stable places where people can grieve and come back to themselves.

That’s all I have to offer. That is all I know.

I do not work in the field of reality. I work, and have trained myself, to explore the ranges of non-reality, and the ranges of human emotion.

I am not a fantasist. I don’t long to fly a dragon or imagine myself a princess or a fairy. But I can completely imagine this should I need to… imagination is fun. Acting is fun.

But life these days is asking me to please put down my favorite blinders and look. And I don’t want to. I don’t want to see things that mean one and one equal two.

A friend of mine says that change is inevitable. And that life is constant change. And I’m fine with that.

But my heart needs to stop hurting. And it hurts because it is a child’s heart. And it’s a child’s heart because it remains ever hopeful that people will rise to their best selves.

So… I guess I shall remain heartbroken. Because I cannot give up hope in mankind. It is simply not in my nature.

20 or so years ago, I took a giant risk - I left “All My Children” where I had become a “legacy character” and took a role that was the complete opposite of her. The part of “Dixie” was that of a country girl who aspired to be a part of something greater, only to find her reach exceeded her grasp. But she got the real jackpot, true love with a man known for his philandering ways (“Tad the Cad”). She had a deep West Virginia accent and tended to dress out of second hand bin, or at the very least, simply. She had one child, Adam Jr, who was everything to her.

This character, “Rosanna,” was an educated high society business woman who took what she wanted (including revenge) wherever she saw fit. She was elegant and well spoken, dressed out of Bergdorfs, could have everything or anything she wanted but children. Her love life was always a mess. She liked smart scoundrels, too, men who made her laugh. But the man she loved the most had a broken moral compass and broke her heart time and again.

I played both these roles in NYC, and although the work was so hard it was like actor boot camp (you try memorizing 20-30 pages a day, 4-5 days a week, playing heavy material and giving a good performance each time), there was a great camaraderie (we laughed our asses off) and unspoken agreement among the cast that stuck. That agreement was: do good work.

The writers, producers and directors of these shows had the same pride and caring when it came to our shared efforts. 

I’m grateful for everything these shows gave me. Grateful I got to act for a living. Grateful the teams behind these shows understood what I brought to the table and supported it. Gave me a chance to shine. Thank you so, so much.

One of the things I like to help actors with is how to handle an audience. One trick I came up with is this:

I have the actors get on the empty stage, (when the theater is empty) and I tell them to imagine they have a big whip in their hands. Like a bullwhip.

I tell them to imagine themselves as a lion tamer, and the audience full of lions.

And then I tell them to practice “cracking the whip.” Literally. Get their stance strong, feel the whip in their hand, and then “CRACK IT!”

This is a hell of a lot of fun.

Now of course, we LOVE the lions. No one need get hurt here, but you have to learn how to feel IN CONTROL. 

Once an audience has the control you are screwed, as an actor. 

Same if you are on a set. You need to have control over yourself, to know where the camera is and be able to feel a sense of power and choice. Michael Caine’s “Acting on Film” is where you can find some fantastic information on this. Choice and control based on knowledge of how the camera sees.

In 2015 I got to interview the lovely Araeia Robinson, who was directing shorts and beautiful fashion and music videos at the time. Her creativity and career have expanded wildly but I’m so glad to have been able to spend time recording her wisdom early in her career.

She said, “women live in two worlds. The man’s world, and our world.” I never forgot this, and to this day I contemplate what this means to me.

I think there is a certain mystery to being in a female identity. Some might say it comes with the ability to bear children and the connection to the earth it gives us. Others say that it’s more of a spiritual identity. Still others say it’s cultural and is different from place to place.

What I tried to do with my film is show that, regardless of gender identity, people who identify as female and directors have a vision. And that vision deserves to have space made for it in the world, even if it’s expressed in a unique way.

Personally, I like to make beauty wherever I go. Whether that’s in a friendship, an apartment, a drawing, a performance, a play or a film. Something that gives pleasure, soothes, gives the viewer that visual “ahhhh” feeling.

I think when there is esthetic beauty, the words of a story ride into the mind of the viewer with less confusion.

I wonder sometimes if I should’ve been an illustrator or a set designer. I cannot help that I am good at many things. For me, it’s just playing. Pleasantville, NY is a very pleasant place. It projects an innocent charm that my child self finds delight in. I rely on people who light up their houses, because lights are a gesture.

In another era we put candles in our windows. A light to help the lost find their way home.

Whatever your faith, one’s faith in humanity and its capacity for greatness, for excellence, for exquisite expression must not be dimmed. Neither must we lose the simple gestures - the quiet help one can give a person in need.

This might gross some people out, but I picked up a dead pigeon and took it out of the street the other day. I couldn’t let it lay there and watch as its body was run over by car after car.

So I found a plastic shopping bag on the street and picked up its body - a solid little thing of feathers and bone. A man looked at me, somewhat surprised. I looked down and saw its little white intestines were exposed, so I wrapped it up more carefully.  Then I put it in one of those trash containers that look a bit like a mailbox so no one digging in the trash would have an unfortunate surprise.

I felt no horror. I wasn’t grossed out. It was a body, as holy as any other body. And it deserved a little dignity. 

Perhaps I was a war nurse in another life. Perhaps I should’ve been one in this life. If my childhood was different I might’ve been. But I’m grateful that I can love dead things like that. Care for them. We all need to know that our lives matter, and that we will all take care of one another right to the end. 

Wishing you a day with a spark of light in it.

This is my great grandmother, Lucina Flores Barre. She was born in Mexico and married Percy Barre, a Frenchman. They had a beautiful flower farm together in the Guadalupe Valley in Northern Baja. An area known now as Mexico’s Wine Country for its rich soil.

Really. Just about an hour south of the California border is some of the most lush, green land you could imagine. Follow the latitude and it will take you around the world to Jerusalem, also known for its rich soil and verdant land.

When I was a child I was obsessed with open, green land and Adobe villas with a center courtyard. I dreamt about them, thought about them. I imagined they must be the perfect place to live.

I wasn’t raised knowing I was part Mexican. I didn’t find this out until after my mother died. And then it took a while to sink in. It’s like a ghost memory, something I only know because it runs through me without my having any say in the matter.

Holidays make me think about family. I wish more than anything I had known Lucina, and my grandmother who is my namesake, Katherine. Alas, they died before I was born.  I wonder if they feel the same about me.

There was a flickering light above my desk this morning. Perhaps someone was visiting.

Good morning! I found my notes from 1992 when I studied with Curt Dempster - the Artistic Director of Ensemble Studio Theater at the time - and they are sooooo good.

One thing he said is sticking with me in such a big way. I thought perhaps you’d like hearing it:

“The theme of every mythology is that there is an invisible plane supporting the visible one.”

I remember studying a fair amount of Joesph Campbell’s “The Power of Myth” at this time, fascinated by his desire to find the common thread that all mythology was linked by. His studies became a book called “The Heroes Journey” and the movie industry jumped onboard to apply this structure to films like “Star Wars.”

However, what I am finding now is that although there are strong behavior commonalities and life rituals that link us, it is only the specificity of the individual life, through experiencing the individual dream if you will, that allows us to see that commonality.

As Michael Howard would say, “the more personal, the more universal.”

So it’s important to find and honor your personal journey, your personal mythology, whatever that may be. The people who have done this with great commitment are the great writers, those who toil in theater and literature. They are constantly digging into their hidden worlds to come back with treasure for us.

One of my favorite quotes is by Coleridge:

“He looked at his Soul with a Telescope. What seemed all irregular, he saw and showed to be beautiful Constellations; and he added to the Consciousness hidden worlds within worlds.”
— Samuel Taylor Coleridge 1772 – 1834 

I ran across this at a moment when the web between the worlds was thin. 

I’m always happier when I can cross this veil and come back with understanding. It’s a beautiful experience I highly recommend. No one can do it for you. But seek and you will find!

Happy Thursday!

When I was a girl, I worked. For some reason, I was chosen to work with some incredible people. This is a shot from a 1983 TV Movie called “Who Will Love My Children” starring Ann-Margret and Frederick Forrest. The story was about a poor woman who was dying of cancer and her alcoholic husband and how they decided to give all the children to other families. (It was based on a true story).

It was something special to watch those actors work. They were clear, devoted, and deeply sensitive to each other and us children.

The director, John Erman, just let us be. Let us breathe in the scenes. I felt I could just be myself and that was enough. It was a gift.

I am in a unique moment in my life, where I am having to face that I am a little different, and am going through a rather difficult process in accepting how that is okay. 

I am a soft person. I make beauty. I must live in a beautiful environment or I get very unhappy. It doesn’t have to be full of expensive things, but the esthetic is important to me.

Vibe is important. Humor is essential. Room for the most tender of feelings almost a law. There is no room for cruelty, ridicule, disrespect or hate.

This is not being overly sympathetic. It is loving. It is making space for others. I’ve always been able to do that. I don’t know why.
